  "text": "strains have only limited change, from 0.8 to 1.2, depending on the specific growth conditions and initial strains [CITATION_1] . Experimentally, it has been found that some specific viruses can adapt to higher temperatures in a relatively short time (400 generations for bacteria phage G4, for example [CITATION_2] et al. 2006) , given a generation time of a couple of hours, this means that they can adapt to novel environment in several days to a few months. Thus according to our model, fever might not always be the most effective mechanism for viral infections all the time, although it still may be effective to some viral infections. This agrees with common knowledge that fever response is more often caused by bacterial infection, since during the time course of a fever, which is around a few days, bacteria can hardly adjust to the new thermal environment, and are therefore likely to get eliminated.",
